---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
const title = 'About | SexualHarassmentCalc';
const description = 'About SexualHarassmentCalc: editorial mission, scope, and what the site is and is not.';
---
<BaseLayout title={title} description={description}>
  <h1>About SexualHarassmentCalc</h1>
  <p><em>Reviewed by Devin Bertram (DB), Editor-in-Chief &mdash; EEOC Practice. Updated May 2026.</em></p>

  <p>
    SexualHarassmentCalc is an independent educational resource on workplace sexual harassment claims under Title VII of the
    Civil Rights Act of 1964 and parallel state laws. The site exists because most people researching a harassment claim are
    doing so for the first time, under stress, and the legitimate online resources are either dense agency PDFs or law-firm marketing pages.
    We sit in between: practitioner-written, plain-language, and openly informational.
  </p>

  <h2>What the site does</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Provides a calculator that returns an educational settlement range based on claim type, severity, employer size, employment action, jurisdiction, income, and tenure.</li>
    <li>Documents how the range is constructed on the <a href="/methodology">methodology page</a>, with the statutes, regulations, and Supreme Court cases that drive each component.</li>
    <li>Publishes deep guides on <a href="/case-types">claim types</a>, <a href="/guides/what-to-do-after-workplace-harassment">post-incident steps</a>, and <a href="/guides/common-sexual-harassment-claim-misconceptions">common misconceptions</a>.</li>
    <li>Maintains an <a href="/editorial">editorial standards</a> page identifying every reviewer by name and credential.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>What the site is not</h2>
  <p>
    SexualHarassmentCalc is <strong>not a law firm</strong>. We do not represent readers, do not accept cases, and do not generate
    referrals to a captive panel of attorneys. Reading the site or emailing us does not create an attorney-client relationship.
    Nothing on the site is legal advice for any specific situation. Sexual harassment cases turn on facts, evidence, jurisdiction,
    and deadlines that only a licensed attorney can evaluate against your circumstances. Talk to one before any statute of
    limitations passes.
  </p>

  <h2>Who runs it</h2>
  <p>
    The site is produced by The Click Lab, an independent editorial group that publishes practitioner-reviewed legal-information
    sites. Editorial direction sits with <strong>Devin Bertram (DB)</strong>, EEOC Practice &amp; Title VII Lead, with contributing
    state-statutes reference work by <strong>Harlow Pace (HP)</strong>. Full bios and credentials are on the
    <a href="/editorial">editorial team</a> page.
  </p>

  <h2>How we make money</h2>
  <p>
    Display advertising through Google AdSense (publisher ID pub-6434377544325972). We do not sell leads to law firms, do not run
    affiliate links to lawyer-marketing services, and do not accept paid placement in our guides. If an attorney or firm is
    referenced on the site, it is because the case or the public filing is legally relevant, not because money changed hands.
  </p>

  <h2>Contact</h2>
  <p>
    Corrections, content suggestions, and press inquiries: <a href="mailto:hey@theclicklab.agency">hey@theclicklab.agency</a>. We
    do not answer specific legal questions about reader situations; use the <a href="https://www.eeoc.gov/field-office">EEOC field-office
    locator</a> or a licensed employment attorney for that.
  </p>
</BaseLayout>
